    body: 'What is the difference between narrow and wide transformations in Spark? Why does it matter for performance?',
    answer: 'Narrow transformations (map, filter, select) operate on data within a single partition — no data movement across the network. Wide transformations (groupBy, join, distinct, repartition) require a shuffle — data moves between partitions/nodes. Shuffles are expensive: serialization, disk I/O, and network transfer. Performance implication: minimize wide transformations. When a groupBy is unavoidable, repartition on the groupBy key first to co-locate related data, reducing shuffle volume. Use AQE to let Spark auto-optimize shuffle partitions at runtime.',
