    body: 'What is the difference between useMemo and useCallback? Give concrete examples of when each actually helps vs. when it hurts.',
    answer: 'useMemo memoizes a computed value: const sortedList = useMemo(() => expensiveSort(data), [data]) — skips the sort if data has not changed. useCallback memoizes a function reference: const handleClick = useCallback(() => doThing(id), [id]) — useful when the function is passed as a prop to a memoized child component (React.memo does not help if the function prop has a new reference every render). When they HURT: wrapping cheap operations adds overhead (closure creation, dependency comparison). Rule: profile first. Only memoize when you have confirmed the operation is the bottleneck. Premature memoization is a common React anti-pattern.',
