    body: 'What is the difference between an S3 bucket policy, IAM policy, and S3 ACL? Which takes precedence?',
    answer: 'IAM Policy: attached to a user/role — defines what AWS resources that identity can access. S3 Bucket Policy: resource-based policy attached to the bucket — can grant access to cross-account users or AWS services without IAM changes. S3 ACL: legacy, object-level access control — avoid for new architectures (AWS recommends disabling ACLs with Object Ownership setting). Precedence: explicit DENY in any policy wins. Otherwise, access is allowed if EITHER an IAM policy OR a bucket policy grants it (same-account). Cross-account: BOTH the IAM policy in the requester account AND the bucket policy must allow access. Best practice: use bucket policies + IAM, disable ACLs, block public access by default.',
