    tech: [],
    experience: '4-8 years',
    answer: 'MVCC: instead of locking rows for reads, PostgreSQL keeps multiple versions of rows. Writers create new row versions (with transaction IDs). Readers see the version that was committed before their transaction started. Writers never block readers, readers never block writers. Old versions cleaned up by VACUUM. Each transaction has a snapshot of \'visible\' rows. This enables high read-write concurrency.',
