    tech: [],
    experience: '2-5 years',
    answer: 'For small tables, sequential scan is faster than index scan: index scan needs to read index B-tree pages then fetch heap pages (random I/O). Sequential scan reads table pages sequentially (predictable I/O). Postgres estimates sequential scan cheaper when table fits in memory or row count is low. Force index with SET enable_seqscan=off (testing only). Usually, Postgres is right — don\'t override without benchmarking.',
