    tech: [],
    experience: '4-8 years',
    answer: 'CAP: Consistency (all nodes see same data), Availability (every request gets response), Partition tolerance (works despite network splits). Can only have 2 of 3. CA (no partition tolerance): traditional RDBMS like MySQL — consistent and available as long as no network splits (single node or trusted network). CP: HBase, ZooKeeper — consistent but may reject requests during partition. AP: Cassandra, DynamoDB — always available, eventually consistent.',
