    tech: ['Java'],
    experience: '3-6 years',
    answer: 'Most objects die young (the "weak generational hypothesis"), so young-gen collections are frequent but fast — they scan a small region and most objects are garbage, so there\'s little to copy. Old-gen collections are rarer but slower since they scan a much larger heap region with mostly-live objects. The assumption breaks down when an application has high object promotion (objects surviving multiple young-gen cycles due to being held too long, e.g. large caches or memory leaks) — this triggers frequent, expensive full GCs and is usually the real cause of "GC pause" production issues, not the young-gen collections themselves.',
